              &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Translation. An Anthology of  Essays from Dryden to Derrida</em>. Chicago and London: The University of Chicago<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Press: 144-51<br>
              Kristeva, Julia. 1991. <em>Strangers to Ourselves</em> (tr. L. S. Roudiez). New York and London: Harvester Wheatsheaf.<br>
              Seferis, George. 1982. <em>Complete Poems</em> (tr. E. Keeley and Philip Sherrard). London: Anvil Press Poetry.<br>
  &ndash; &ndash;. 1974. <em>A Poet&rsquo;s Journal. Days of 1945-1951</em> (tr. A.  Anagnostopoulos). Cambridge, Massachusetts: The Belknap<br>
  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Press of Harvard University Press.<br>
              Vayenas, Nasos. 1989. <em>Poiisi kai Metafrasi</em> [Poetry and  Translation]. Athens: Stigmi.</p>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
            <div>
              <div id="edn1">
                <p><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1" title="">1.</a> The title of this essay is taken from &lsquo;Only the Common Miracle&rsquo;, a  poem in Richard Berengarten&rsquo;s sequence <em>Black Light</em>. For the most recent monolingual English  publication of this sequence, see Berengarten [1] 2008. For the first English  editions, see Burns: 1983. Some references in this essay are to the bilingual  Anglo-Greek edition of <em>Black Light</em>, (Burns 2005), entitled <em>Mavro Fos</em>,  translated by Nasos Vayenas and Ilias Layios, both poets in their own right.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn2">
                <p><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2" title="">2.</a>&nbsp; In June 2008, Richard Burns  changed his name to Richard Berengarten. This change was announced in notes in  the first five volumes of his <em>Selected Writings</em> (Salt, Cambridge, November 2008), such as the  following: &lsquo;Richard Berengarten used to be known as Richard Burns . . . [H]e now repossesses the family name of  his father, the cellist and saxophonist, Alexander Berengarten&rsquo; (Berengarten [1]: sleeve notes). &nbsp;Henceforward, in references to the poet  himself, this essay adheres to the name Berengarten. </p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn3">
                <p><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3" title="">3.</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;During the period that intervened between my  first and second readings of the bilingual edition of <em>Black Light</em>, Ilias Layios, one of the book&rsquo;s two translators, died  unexpectedly in Athens in  2005.&nbsp; In 2006, I also learned of the  death of my close personal family friend, Kyria Christoula.<strong> </strong></p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn4">
                <p><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4" title="">4.</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;This element in the text itself could, at  least partly, account for the affinity I felt with the book at my own time of  loss.<strong><u> </u></strong></p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn5">
                <p><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5" title="">5.</a>&nbsp; &nbsp; Hereafter all references to the original <em>Black Light</em> will be made in the format (Berengarten [1]: page number), and will be inserted  in the body of the text.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn6">
                <p><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6" title="">6.</a> &nbsp;&nbsp;In Greek criticism, Seferis&rsquo; &lsquo;Kichli&rsquo; [&lsquo;Thrush&rsquo;] is considered to be nothing  less than &ldquo;the Greek equivalent of <em>The Waste Land</em>&rdquo; (Vayenas 1989: 99).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn7">
                <p><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7" title="">7.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;However, Berengarten is careful to add  the English meaning of these words in his notes to the poem: &lsquo;<em>t&aacute;vli</em>:backgammon; <em>ts&iacute;pouro</em>: an anis drink, like ouzo; <em>sk&eacute;to,  m&eacute;tno,  glyk&iacute;  vrast&oacute;</em>:  sugarless, medium, sweet-boiled (terms used for coffee): <em>nichter&iacute;dhes</em>:bats.&rsquo; (Berengarten [1]: 224)</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn8">
                <p><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8" title="">8.</a> &nbsp;&nbsp;For further thoughts on the idea of the &lsquo;original&rsquo;, see Filippakopoulou 2005:  47-48, quoted above.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn9">
                <p><a href="#_ednref9" name="_edn9" title="">9.</a> &nbsp;&nbsp;Let us  remember that Seferis himself was effectively a Greek living on the mainland  after the forced exile from his childhood homeland, Asia Minor (Ionia), in 1922. His poetry is, in a way, a poetry of  exile; see the introductory point made by his editors (Seferis1982<em>:</em> xvii).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn10">
                <p><a href="#_ednref10" name="_edn10" title="">10.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp; In a personal response to  the author (April 3, 2008), Richard Berengarten has noted that if the epigraph taken from Seferis is  &ldquo;understated&rdquo;, it was chosen to be so, deliberately. And he continues as  follows: &ldquo;because, for my purposes, I needed to highlight the simplest elements  of Seferis&rsquo; line and so to remove them from their (from my point of view,  over-specified) surrounding context. So perhaps the part quoted does <em>appear</em> &lsquo;uninteresting&rsquo;. But I&rsquo;ve always thought the whole of this line to be among  Seferis&rsquo; most wonderful, most fabulous achievements, for its purity of music  (with the sibilant sounds of ships&rsquo; sirens) and its transparent simplicity, as  well as its centred, embodied love of the aural and visual [&hellip;] I suppose you  could even say that my poem, in some respects, attempts to retranslate back (i.e.  both &lsquo;honour&rsquo; and&nbsp; &lsquo;give back&rsquo;) the &lsquo;open  secret&rsquo; of physicality redolent in this epigraph.&rdquo; The entire line by Seferis  reads as follows: &ldquo;&Sigma;&phi;&upsilon;&rho;&#943;&zeta;&omicron;&upsilon;&nu; &tau;&alpha; &kappa;&alpha;&rho;&#940;&beta;&iota;&alpha; &tau;&#974;&rho;&alpha; &pi;&omicron;&upsilon; &beta;&rho;&alpha;&delta;&iota;&#940;&zeta;&epsilon;&iota; &sigma;&tau;&omicron;&nu; &Pi;&epsilon;&iota;&rho;&alpha;&iota;&#940;,&rdquo; which is  transliterated as &ldquo;Sfir&iacute;zoun ta kar&aacute;via t&oacute;ra pou vrathi&aacute;zei ston Pieirai&aacute;&rdquo;  &ndash;&ldquo;The ships hoot now that dusk falls on Piraeus.&rdquo; (&lsquo;In the manner of G.  S.&rsquo;,&nbsp; Seferis 1982: 110-111).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn11">
                <p><a href="#_ednref11" name="_edn11" title="">11.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;This is  especially so in the translation, because in Greek all nouns are  gender-specific &ndash; most either masculine or feminine, with a smaller number that  are neuter. Thus, when one is translating out of English, gender  differentiation sometimes accounts for unexpected results in terms of meaning:  for example, the &ldquo;[k]ing sun&rdquo; is male, the city is female, and &ldquo;darling evening&rdquo;  is female. This means that the narrator&rsquo;s enamoured adoration of these elements  can unexpectedly vary hints of heterosexual or unidirectional attraction. Roman  Jakobson, among others, has commented on the poetic implications and  mythological connections bound to the gender of inanimate nouns (Jakobson 1992:  149-51).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn12">
                <p><a href="#_ednref12" name="_edn12" title="">12.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;For a  discussion of statues in Seferis&rsquo; poetry, see Beaton 1991: 46-49.</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn13">
                <p><a href="#_ednref13" name="_edn13" title="">13.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lsquo;Cicadas  (I)&rsquo; finishes with the couplet &ldquo;[t]hey are hollowing a cave out of these night  covered hills/ and they will hole us up in it, until we drown in darkness&rdquo; (Berengarten [1]: 162).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn14">
                <p><a href="#_ednref14" name="_edn14" title="">14.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lsquo;Cicadas&rsquo;  is the grammatical subject of a string of verbs: &ldquo;they groan like the dead&rdquo;,  &ldquo;they whine like the unborn outside my window&rdquo;, &ldquo;hover over the surrounding  hills&rdquo;, &ldquo;argue my destiny&rdquo;, [are] &ldquo;creaking under the snow&rdquo;, &ldquo;breaking up  glaciers&rdquo;, &ldquo;roped like slaves, heaving slabs of silence into pyramids of music  to celebrate a pharaoh across deserts on the ocean&rsquo;s chilly floor&rdquo; (ibid:  171-172).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn15">
                <p><a href="#_ednref15" name="_edn15" title="">15.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;In an early poem, &lsquo;Guest&rsquo;, we read: &ldquo;He said he had opened himself to the  light, / that the light was a poem, was everywhere presence, / a silent  language with its grammar of waves and particles / of which our speeches were  dialects [&hellip;]&rdquo; (Burns 1980: 21).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn16">
                <p><a href="#_ednref16" name="_edn16" title="">16.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;Elsewhere, I  have discussed the clear deviation of Nasos Vayenas,<strong> </strong>who reinstates  syntactical order by omitting the comma in the lines &ldquo;[a]ngelic and black,  light&hellip;/ Angelic and black, day&rdquo;, the epigraph of Berengarten&rsquo;s &lsquo;In Memory of  George Seferis (I)&rsquo; (Berengarten [1]: 153), as a mark of &ldquo;a predominantly <em>native</em> experience of the Greek light&rdquo;, perhaps even of&nbsp;  &ldquo;<em>Seferis&rsquo; verses</em>&rdquo;(Filippakopoulou 2005: 50).</p>
              </div>
              <div id="edn17">
                <p><a href="#_ednref17" name="_edn17" title="">17.</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lsquo;Radiance,  palpable. In memory of Ilias Layios&rsquo; (sic), <a href="http://www.richardburns.eu/site/From_Notness.html">http://www.richardburns.eu/site/From_Notness.html</a>.</p>
              </div>
